summary:
Jon x Sansa Hollywood AU
Director Jon Snow, who is still riding high after giving us yet another massive hit, Good Queen...
body:
Jon x Sansa Hollywood AU

Director Jon Snow, who is still riding high after giving us yet another massive hit, Good Queen Alysanne, is rumoured to be dating his leading lady, Sansa Stark. It is a good time to remind our readers that Stark’s casting as Queen Alysanne, had been very controversial at the time, given it was her first major role in a movie and also due to constant online attacks from ex-boyfriend, Joffery Baratheon. We are glad that Sansa not only proved her critics wrong but exceeded expectations of many in and outside the industry. In a hilarious turn of events, since the movie’s record breaking success and Sansa’s first major award, many have started trolling the famous ex online using the hash-tag “Sansa Stark Defense Squad”.

Fans had been “shipping” Snow and Stark ever since the footage of them arguing passionately was leaked during the promotions. Many people took to twitter to express how the brief video was dripping with sexual tension, everything from their body gestures to their facial expressions were analysed and the ship name Jonsa was decided upon. The rumors about Jonsa were then further fueled after Dolores Edd, who plays Lord Commander, revealed in a candid interview with Melisandre, that Snow was referred to as “the beast” on the set by rest of the cast and crew of GQA given his constant outbursts at “Any man who even dared to mention Sansa’s name.”

Both Jon and Sansa have not officially denied or confirmed the news but Margaery Tyrell, one of Sansa’s closest friends, has been dropping many not so subtle hints on her social media stories…..

summary: Do you think it matters if Jon come back to life or not. Ned, Robb, Quentyn and tywin all die but the story continues.
question: Do you think it matters if Jon come back to life or not. Ned, Robb, Quentyn and tywin all die but the story continues.
answer:
Jon Snow is coming back. Between the set up of Rh'ollor resurrection magic (Beric/Lady Stoneheart), Melisandre seeing only snow in her flames, and no one available to deal with the poltical powderkeg at the Wall (wildings on the South side, Stannis’s men, Wun-Wun).

Jon Snow staying dead doesn’t compel the narrative action in the same manner as the other characters. Tywin and Ned dying forces their influence into their children alone and what their personal legacy ends up being: the Lannisters destroy each other within hours while the Starks inspire loyalty in a dead winter march. Robb and the Red Wedding again raises the stakes and forces the other protagonists into more dire growth (Sansa in the Vale/Arya in Braavos). Quentyn dies blocking the potential alliance with Dorne and setting up the seeds of another potential Targaryen civil war.

All those deaths serve a greater narrative function; the resurrection of Jon Snow will do the same.

But it have a high cost.

summary: I know people have defended it
title: I know people have defended it
body:
but just short and succinct notes on why I ship Jonsa:

- they work as a -team-
- they exude ‘comfort’ rather than ‘passion’/’lust’, or some ~opposites attract~ basic attraction
- before you try to school me on ‘incest’ or their ‘brother/sister’ relationship, I have a brother, and trust me, Jon is NOT acting like a brother (those stares? handholding?? forehead kiss??! If Robb did it to Sansa, I will be (just being honest here) repulsed.) I am against incest in real life, very much so. 

- Jon/Sansa is not Jaime/Cersei, they’re stronger parallels to Jaime/Brienne

- Bryan Cogman, you know, writer/producer, already stated that Jon and Sansa viewed each other as non-siblings when they were young, they weren’t close, hence they don’t have the familiarity/bond brothers and sisters have. Come on, so many posts have already dissected this to the letter. Plus, Jon is her cousin, which is allowable in medieval times/Game of Thrones. I mean, Tywin Lannister was head over heels over his cousin/wife/mom of Cersei, Jaime and (??) Tyrion

- wolf bits, chokeholds, redheads + princes

- as a writer, the romantic structure (or stealthy lack of) D&D are using to build them up. Lots of lies and deceit going on around here, very GoT like

- George RR Martin’s original outline, which has protagonist Jon falling in love with a girl he thought was his sister (previously named Arya), cue internal strife and anguish, then relief when they find out they’re just cousins. (compare to the Jon/D*ny strife of omg-I-banged-a-girl-who-I’m-actually-related-to-god-damn) 

THINGS that I think will NOT happen:

- No Jonsa wedding, because of the dire situation Westeros is in. Night King, Targaryen restoration/three-way-war - they won’t have the luxury of grand weddings. We might get Jon pledging his loyalty to the North, maybe some romantic dialogue scenes, but no wedding.

- I also think they won’t have a sex scene anytime soon. I mean, season 7 hardly had one (except a couple, and a major one, like…boatbang lol). The way things are getting hectic, I don’t think they’re going to include one. Maybe hint at it, I dunno. 


At the rate things are going, I actually think no one’s going to have some sexy time soon. War, dragons, dragon zombies, etc.  But hey, if Jon and D*ny found time on a boat…well, people can be resourceful.

That ends my rant. Peace out.

blog.name: chitowngirl-12
blog.title: Chicago Diva
blog.description: I'm a fan of Jon, the North, and the Starks.  Not a Jonsa, but an ally because they are nice, rational people unlike other parts of GOT fandom that will remain nameless.  (Apparently I'm also a sexist crazy person for having bad, ungood opinions about Daenerys Targaryen!  And I also set up alts and post anonymous comments and talk to myself on AO3...  Sarc off.  Yeah, fandom is pissing me off right now.)

summary: Daenerys:  Servant, attend to me and tell me what to do about the war I’m currently losing. Jon stays and spouts off some...
body:
Daenerys:  Servant, attend to me and tell me what to do about the war I’m currently losing.

Jon stays and spouts off some meaningless gibberish about burning stuff with dragons.

Jonerys fan logic: OMG, Dany just gave Jon complete control of her armies.  See.  She totally values his advice.

The rest of us:  Where are you getting that take from that scene?
